  "chunk_index": 21,
  "summary": "Harold, Alfred, Sedrick, and Cedric argue regarding Lucy Ashebrook, who recently discovered a sarcophagus inside a long warehouse. Harold expresses suspicion toward Lucy’s attitude and the suspicious ease of her discovery, while Cedric suggests she may not be who she claims to be. Alfred expresses his intention to investigate her ulterior motives.\n\nDuring a tea gathering, Lucy meets with Miss Marple. Lucy mentions she has two brothers in London and a brother named Cedric, a painter living in Ibiza. Miss Marple shares stories regarding Lucy's clever childhood and her own life. The gathering is interrupted by the arrival of Brian and Dr. Campbell. After discussing his medical practice and the regulation of doctors, Dr. Campbell leaves with Emma to visit her father. Following their departure, Sedrick remarks that Emma is a \"spinster by nature,\" prompting a reaction from Miss Marple, who hints at a thought the men do not understand. Cedric makes a joke about the family being well-off \"except for one murder case,\" which angers Harold. Miss Marple compares Cedric to a man named Thomas Idle, who inherited money after his father's death.\n\nLater, Lucy drives Miss Marple home. Upon her return, Alfred intercepts Lucy's car. During the drive to the garage, Alfred tells Lucy that she is wasting her intelligence on domestic chores. He suggests she use her cleverness to circumvent rules and power, proposing that they work together because of her ability to gain people's trust.",
